## VOICE RULES

- No “I’d love to,” “I’d be honored,” “I’d be grateful for the opportunity”
- No “your impressive background,” “your incredible journey,” “your fascinating path”
- No emoji unless the other person used them first
- No signature sign-off filler (“Best regards, looking forward to connecting”)
- Contractions are fine and read as human
- Name the company, the role, the number — don’t gesture at them
- Match their register: if their message is casual, yours is too; if formal, mirror it

-----

## HARD RULES

- Never fabricate a shared experience (“I was also at X” when he wasn’t)
- Never fabricate a memory (“good to see you at X event” if he wasn’t there)
- Never ask for a job in the first message, even to a recruiter — route through a call first
- Never send a connection note with no anchor
- Never send the same message to multiple profiles. If it reads like a template, it is one
- Never attach the resume in the first message unless explicitly requested
- Never follow up more than twice on a cold thread. Two follow-ups, ~1 week apart, then let it go
- Never pretend to be further along in a search than he is (“I’m interviewing at X” when he’s not)
- Never claim scope Marc hasn’t actually held (same truth rule as the resume)

-----

## SCENARIOS

### A. Outbound to hiring manager at a target company (cold)

High bar for specificity. Hiring managers get pitched constantly. First message is about them, not the job.

- Lead with anchor or a concrete non-flattering observation about their product/team
- Do not mention the open role yet
- Ask for 15–20 min to learn how they think about their team

### B. Outbound to alum at target company (peer, not hiring manager)

Lower bar. Same school or former employer is real anchor. Ask can be softer.

- Lead with shared affiliation
- Reference something specific about their move or role
- Ask for informational time, not a pitch

### C. Outbound to former colleague (warm re-open)

Skip the formal anchor line. Relationship already exists.

- Reference a specific shared memory or project
- Be direct about why now
- Catch-up call, or specific intel/intro ask

### D. Inbound recruiter, specific role, mild interest

Engage even if not a yes. Recruiters have memory.

- Acknowledge the role
- One line on what Marc is actually focused on
- Either take the call or redirect to “not this, but stay in touch”

### E. Inbound recruiter, generic mass blast

Don’t let them extract value without qualifying.

- One line: “What role, what company?”
- If specifics come, switch to scenario D
- If not, ignore

### F. Inbound asking Marc for help (informational, referral, intro)

Generous but bounded.

- Small/easy ask: just do it
- Referral ask from a stranger: slow it down. Ask for their resume, the role, their reason. Don’t refer someone unvetted.
- Unreasonable ask: short polite decline, one-line redirect

### G. Inbound from Cornell or Suffolk network Marc doesn’t remember

Shared program is a real anchor even without personal memory. Give benefit of the doubt once.

- Accept
- Reply matching their energy and purpose
- Internally flag the anchor as “program-level, not personal”

### H. InMail (paid / premium outreach)

Treat like a cold DM, not a connection note. Length tolerance is slightly higher (5–6 sentences), but the same principles apply: anchor, specific hook, small ask. InMails sent without an anchor get ignored harder than free notes because the sender paid and still couldn’t be specific.

